Project Background¶

In this project I'll be training a model to identify the presence of cancer cells in histopathologic images. These images are sampled from the PatchCamelyon dataset which is a large collection of histopathologic scans from lymph node sections. Identifying cancer cells in these images would be evidence that a patient's cancer has spread to the lymph nodes.

Data Problem¶

This is a supervised classification problem with 2 class labels: 0 (no signs of cancer cells), and 1 (presence of cancer cells). The model of choice to work this problem is a convolutional neural network (CNN) which are one of the best types of models used for image classification tasks. In this project I'll be defining a custom CNN architecture, and training it all using the Tensorflow and Keras libraries.

Measurement¶

The metrics used for model evaluation are accuracy (% of classifications that are correct), and AUC (area under the ROC curve). The latter is also used as the test evaluation metric in this Kaggle competition, so is of high importance in this project.

# Displays the histopathological image(s) matching the given records, and highlights the region which was checked for the presence of cancer cells
def show_img(images_df, debug = False):
    img_names = images_df['id']
    img_labels = images_df['label']
    n = len(img_names)
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, n, figsize = (4*n, 4))
    
    for i, img_n in enumerate(img_names):
        img_path = '/kaggle/input/histopathologic-cancer-detection/train/' + img_n + '.tif'
        img_array = cv2.imread(img_path)

        if (debug):
            print("Showing image: " + img_n + ".tif with label: " + str(img_labels.iloc[i]))
        
        if n == 1:
            ax.imshow(img_array)
        else:
            ax[i].imshow(img_array)

        highlight = patches.Rectangle(xy = (32, 32), width = 32, height = 32, edgecolor = 'red', facecolor = 'none')
        
        if n == 1:
            ax.add_patch(highlight)
        else:
            ax[i].add_patch(highlight)

    img_path = '/kaggle/input/histopathologic-cancer-detection/train/' + img_n + '.tif'

Data Preparation¶

Normalizing the training data¶

It will be easier for the network to recognize patterns in the images if the pixel values are normalized. Here I'm centering all values around zero by subtracting the mean for each image array, and using those to build the training data the model will use.

In [11]:
train_data = np.zeros(shape = (train.shape[0], 96, 96, 3))

for i, img_n in enumerate(train['id']):
    img_path = '/kaggle/input/histopathologic-cancer-detection/train/' + img_n + '.tif'
    img_array = cv2.imread(img_path)

    train_data[i] = img_array - img_array.mean()

train_labels = train['label']

print(train_data.shape)
print(train_labels.shape)

Model Building¶

I experimented with a few different basic model architectures, details of which I explain a few cells down in the Model Architectures & Hyperparameter Tuning section.

The final architecture I'm deciding on will be a simple CNN architecture based on what we've learned in lecture:

  • 2 convolution layers w/ ReLU activation functions
  • a batch normalization layer to regularize and speed up convergence,
  • max pool layer to reduce feature map size,
  • followed by a dense output layer with sigmoid activation function for binary classification.

I'll utilize dropout before the output layer to regularize and help the model generalize better. The optimizer used will be Adam with default parameters. Loss function will be binary cross-entropy which makes the most sense for binary classification problem. I'll also be evaluating using metrics accuracy and AUC.

In [12]:
num_filters = 4
filter_size = (5, 5)
pool_size = (4, 4)
pool_stride = 4
dropout_p = 0.5

model = Sequential()
model.add(Conv2D(num_filters, filter_size, activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Conv2D(num_filters, filter_size, activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Conv2D(num_filters, filter_size, activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Conv2D(num_filters, filter_size, activation = 'relu'))
#model.add(BatchNormalization())
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = pool_size, strides = pool_stride))
model.add(Dropout(rate = dropout_p))
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

model.compile('adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy', 'auc'])

Model Training¶

When fitting the model, I'm using callbacks EarlyStopping and ReduceLROnPlateau.

  • As the name suggests, EarlyStopping interrupts training once it sees a metric (by default validation loss) get worse for a number of epochs. By setting patience = 5, I'm letting it know to do the interruption after 5 consecutive epochs with increasing validation loss. Then, the restore_best_weights = True parameter resets the weights back to the last 'best' performing epoch.
  • ReduceLROnPlateau diminishes the learning rate as the validation loss stagnates. However, in my experience I didn't see this ever kick in before EarlyStopping did so I didn't reap much benefit from it.
In [13]:
es = EarlyStopping(verbose = 1, patience = 5, restore_best_weights = True)
rl = ReduceLROnPlateau(verbose = 1)

results = model.fit(x = train_data, y = train_labels, epochs = 20, validation_split = 0.1, callbacks = [es, rl])

Experimenting with Model Architectures¶

I experimented with different model architectures, # layers, # filters, etc. and compared the resulting training and validation accuracies under each.

Below is a table of the results I collected from changing model architecture. I tried changing the number of convolution layers used (2-4), and testing the usage of a Batch Normalization layer, and Dropout (25%, 50%). I tried all combinations and chose the one with the best validation accuracy.

General findings from experimenting with model architecture¶

  • Using dropout of 25% led to much lower accuracies than using 50%. It seems that if using dropout, it's best to employ a high amount of regularization which 50% does.
  • In most cases, using 3 convolutional layers had worse accuracy than using 2 or 4. I looked for any guidelines suggesting that an even number of conv layers was better than odd, but didn't find documentation on this. It may have been a one-off finding for this particular dataset and model structure.
  • Using Batch Normalization on average increased accuracies, especially the training accuracy. I know Batch Normalization can often improve convergence speed of the algorithm, but didn't expect it to have that much effect on accuracy. However, in the end my model architecture without the batch normalization layer had the highest validation accuracy.

General findings from hyperparameter tuning¶

  • Using only 1 filter led to mcuh lower training & validation accuracy than using any higher number of filters.
  • Using more filters typically led to higher training accuracy, but not always higher validation accuracy which was a sign of overfitting. The 'sweet spot' from my tests looked to be 2 or 3 filters.
  • The highest validation accuracy was achieved by using 2 5x5 filters, and 4x4 pooling size. A very close second was using 2 3x3 filters with 4x4 pooling size.
  • Using a larger pooling size generally led to a higher validation accuracy across the board.

Final Model Performance¶

In [16]:
pred_proba = model.predict(x = train_data).reshape(-1)
actual = train_labels

plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC Curve')
plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')

Conclusions and Next Steps¶

Although I was only able to use a subset of training images out of the whole sample, the model achieved ~80% training and validation accuracies, as well as an AUC over 0.9. Including more training images would very likely have helped improve the metrics, but I felt limited by the fact that the Kaggle kernel kept timing out if I used more images. I couldn't easily tell what the issue was from the logs, so I may need to see what others did on their notebooks to get around this issue, or utilize different methods/libraries.

I believe accuracy could also be improved more by employing a more complex model architecture, but since I am not an expert at this yet yet I would probably want to try a pre-built model such as ResNet or Inception Net first. These are models that have already proven themselves by performing well in the ImageNet image classification competition.
